<div id="p527969" class="post bg1 unreadpost">
<div class="inner"><span class="corners-top"><span></span></span>
<div class="postbody">
<h3><a href="http://peakoil.com/forums/using-convex-lenses-to-make-electricity-t32605.html?sid=fcb9a56ed5264c82bdccd2dded3a0a5c#p527969">Re: Using convex lenses to make electricity?</a></h3>
<p class="author"><a href="http://peakoil.com/forums/post527969.html?sid=fcb9a56ed5264c82bdccd2dded3a0a5c#p527969"><img src="http://peakoil.com/forums/styles/thebeeb/imageset/icon_post_target_unread.gif" width="11" height="9" alt="Unread post" title="Unread post"/></a>by <strong><a href="http://peakoil.com/forums/gnm-u302.html?sid=fcb9a56ed5264c82bdccd2dded3a0a5c">gnm</a></strong> &raquo; Tue 02 Oct 2007, 11:35:08 </p>
<div class="content">Your primary problem would be tracking the sun for correct focus. Hardly a simple way of generating electricity. You could make homemade solar PV panels easier. You also lose efficiency with every conversion (like running a turbine). I would suggest a wind turbine or (if you REALLY want to do the steam punk thing) just use a parabolic trough to concentrate on a pipe. That has been done pretty effectively and even at commercial scales.
<br/>
<br/>-G</div>
<div id="sig527969" class="signature">I Have and will continue to vote against ANY politician who supports the various bailouts. Curse you for selling out our future for status quo now!</div>
