<div class="postbody">
<h3><a href="http://peakoil.com/forums/using-convex-lenses-to-make-electricity-t32605.html?sid=fcb9a56ed5264c82bdccd2dded3a0a5c#p528046">Re: Using convex lenses to make electricity?</a></h3>
<p class="author"><a href="http://peakoil.com/forums/post528046.html?sid=fcb9a56ed5264c82bdccd2dded3a0a5c#p528046"><img src="http://peakoil.com/forums/styles/thebeeb/imageset/icon_post_target_unread.gif" width="11" height="9" alt="Unread post" title="Unread post"/></a>by <strong><a href="http://peakoil.com/forums/fishman-u3226.html?sid=fcb9a56ed5264c82bdccd2dded3a0a5c">Fishman</a></strong> &raquo; Tue 02 Oct 2007, 14:12:44 </p>
<div class="content">Mekrob,
<br/>Excellent idea to start with. The parabolic trough allows greater sunlight space to be concentrated. Imagine a 4 foot lens and the material required to make it vs a 4 foot parabolic mirror, easily made with some plywood and perhaps some mylar. Your collecting system would have to capture the energy, reguiring a black surface, then transfer the heat. Clear water wouldn't capture the energy (maybe a clear tube and a black fluid?)</div>
</div>
