<p class="author"><a href="http://peakoil.com/forums/post528453.html?sid=fcb9a56ed5264c82bdccd2dded3a0a5c#p528453"><img src="http://peakoil.com/forums/styles/thebeeb/imageset/icon_post_target_unread.gif" width="11" height="9" alt="Unread post" title="Unread post"/></a>by <strong><a href="http://peakoil.com/forums/kokoda-u14071.html?sid=fcb9a56ed5264c82bdccd2dded3a0a5c">kokoda</a></strong> &raquo; Wed 03 Oct 2007, 11:09:31 </p>
<div class="content">Surely you have just described a solar hot water system.
<br/>
<br/>Using parabolic mirrors to heat water has been tried on an industrial level ... and been found wanting.
<br/>
<br/>The problem is that sunlight is low density energy and you need to concentrate a lot of it to generate any meaningful amount of power.</div>
</div>
